{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17509062","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17509062"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T12:12:36+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T12:12:36+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11377"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"11377","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11377"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.12,0.02,0.49,0.05,0.33]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4022"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"44133"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4022","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4022"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11377"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"29105"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"926"},{"type":"tags","id":"5826"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"4418"},{"type":"contributions","id":"4425"},{"type":"contributions","id":"11287"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"44133","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/44133"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 30-year-old male is brought by ambulance to the Emergency Department following a high speed motor vehicle accident. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. On examination, his pulse rate is 100/min, blood pressure 130/60mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 99% on room air, and temperature 37.0\u00b0C. His GCS has been 15/15 throughout. He has a positive FAST scan and proceeds to a CT scan which identifies a grade IV splenic injury with an active blush on arterial phase and pooling on portovenous phase, with moderate volume haemoperitoneum.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which of the following is the most appropriate management of this patient\u0027s splenic injury?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Exploratory laparotomy","Massive transfusion pack","Splenic artery angioembolisation","Splenorrhaphy","Splenectomy"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has blunt abdominal trauma, with a CT demonstrating a grade IV splenic injury with vascular injury. In the haemodynamically unstable patient then regardless of injury grade, this patient would require urgent\u003Cstrong\u003E exploratory laparotomy \u003C/strong\u003Efor identification and management of injuries. Management may include \u003Cstrong\u003Esplenectomy\u003C/strong\u003E in the case of a shattered spleen, or splenic salvage techniques such as \u003Cstrong\u003Esplenorrhaphy\u003C/strong\u003E given the increasing awareness of the importance of the spleen\u0027s immunological role.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis patient is haemodynamically normal at presentation but with this injury could deteriorate quickly. In the Emergency Department, IV access and resuscitation would occur prior to transfer to CT if they remain stable. If there was no vascular injury, then\u003Cstrong\u003E \u003C/strong\u003Eobservation alone or observation and transfusion as required would be appropriate. A \u003Cstrong\u003Emassive transfusion pack\u003C/strong\u003E would not be the most appropriate answer in this clinical scenario as the patient is haemodynamically stable. However, this patient has clear evidence of vascular injury with a leak of contrast on arterial phase (blush) indicating active bleeding, and pooling on the portovenous phase, with a haemoperitoneum. This requires intervention: in a stable patient, \u003Cstrong\u003Eangiography and embolisation\u003C/strong\u003E of the bleeding vessel to occlude it is most appropriate. Other indications for embolisation include a traumatic AV fistula and a pseudoaneurysm. There is a chance of failure (especially in the older patient with moderate-large volume haemoperitoneum) or physiological deterioration, therefore these patients require ongoing close observation of vital signs, abdominal exam for peritonism, and haemoglobin monitoring to ensure persistent bleeding is caught early.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Haemodynamically stable patients with splenic vascular injury (active blush, traumatic AV fistula, pseudoaneurysm) should be managed with angioembolisation where available."],"references":["Clements W, Joseph T, Koukounaras J, Goh GS, Moriarty HK, Mathew J, et al. SPLEnic salvage and complications after splenic artery EmbolizatioN for blunt abdomINal trauma: the SPLEEN-IN study. CVIR Endovasc. 2020;3(1):92. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC7719586/","Coccolini, F., Montori, G., Catena, F. et al. Splenic trauma: WSES classification and guidelines for adult and pediatric patients. World J Emerg Surg 12, 40 (2017). https://doi.org/10.1186/s13017-017-0151-4"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"29105"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11377"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"29105","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/29105"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-04-07T16:03:51+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-24T15:31:54+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4022"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"44133"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt"